Recently, I am trying to speed up my connectome predictive modeling code. I found that the matrix operations are the bottleneck. Specifically, I need a faster version of `scale()`. Based on [this blog](A Faster Scale Function | A HopStat and Jump Away (wordpress.com), I decided to benchmark the matrix operations in different packages from [fastverse](https://fastverse.github.io/fastverse/).


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/unnamed-chunk-1_44509ca7986b926675d54ca86ad4acab'}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(collapse)
requireNamespace("bench")
```
:::


# Row Means


::: {.cell hash='index_cache/html/bench-rowMeans_3c1b0abdb4d7a8ab648a1f821f9dda05'}

```{.r .cell-code}
bench <- bench::press(
  nrow = c(10, 100, 1000),
  ncol = c(100, 1000, 10000),
  {
    data <- matrix(rnorm(nrow * ncol), nrow = nrow)
    bench::mark(
      collapse = collapse::fmean(data),
      Rfast = Rfast::colmeans(data),
      matrixStats = matrixStats::colMeans2(data),
      base = .colMeans(data, nrow, ncol)
    )
  }
)
```
:::

::: {.cell .column-page hash='index_cache/html/fig-rowmeans_f3b96267f6df87462fbeac0fd067b5d1'}

```{.r .cell-code}
plot(bench)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Benchmark of row means](index_files/figure-html/fig-rowmeans-1.png){#fig-rowmeans width=768}
:::
:::


